Soccer's Best Managers

By Brandon Velasquez and Miles Dobbins

Introduction¶

With the beginning of a new decade, we can now reflect on the previous one and in this project we will be focusing on that of the football/soccer world. Throughout the 2010s, there are a few managers that come to mind when you think of those who have been hailed as some of the most prolific football minds of the recent generations. With the tools and data available at our disposal we have decided to put that to the test and see who these managers are and how exactly they stack up against the rest of the managers in the 2010s. Since this tutorial will focus on the different managers throughout the 2010s we will be looking at data from the top 3 leagues in the world, the English Premier League, LaLiga Santander, and Bundesliga.

Set Up¶

Listed below are the packages that we will utilize throughout this project. Pandas is used to read in csv files as well as create and fold data inside of their dataframes. Datetime is used to change the formats of dates and times to be easier to manipulate and rearrange. Requests will be used to handle the web scraping for all other incoming data. bs4/BeautifulSoup will be used to read in and make raw HTML and other web scraping data usable. re is used to parse regular expressions to make a more clear and concise data set. The plotting imports are used to create graphs and plots to visually display data. Warnings is imported to help clean up the code.

Data Gathering¶

The bulk of the data we will be using will be from datahub.io(specific link provided below with the rest of the sources) which provides us with all of the statistical game data minus the data of individual players and staff. The player data is negligible throughout the tutorial so we only need to focus on managers and that data is coming from multiple Wikipedia pages(also listed below). While attempting to wrangle the manager data from wikipedia, we found a discrepancy between the available data for the premier league managers and the managers from both other leagues. The premier league wikipedia page showcases all managers in the premier league with some even dating back to the 1970s whereas the Bundesliga and LaLiga Santander manager lists are only available for individual seasons(i.e. 2009-10, 2011-12, etc.) on separate pages. This process will be discussed more in data tidying.

Generating League Datasets¶

To get the game data into a dataframe, there had to be tweaks made to the date to make the data uniform. Somewhere in the data, the format of the date changed, so functions were added to make the dates all uniform. Lastly, a function was added to create a dataframe of game data given a league name.

In [82]:
def fix_date_1(date):
    # Converts YYYY-MM-DD to Datetime
    return dt.datetime.strptime(date, "%Y-%m-%d")

def convert_date(date):
    # Convert DD/MM/YY
    return dt.datetime.strptime(date, "%d/%m/%y")

def fix_date_2(date):
    # Converts DD/MM/YYYY to Datetime
    return dt.datetime.strptime(date, "%d/%m/%Y")


def get_league_data(league_str):
    dfs = [] # holds each each year DataFrame
    
    # iterate from 2009-2010 season up to 2018-2019 season
    for year in range(9, 19):
        year_str = "{0:02d}{1:02d}".format(year, year + 1) # ex: 2018-2019 -> 1819
        _df = pd.read_csv(f"https://datahub.io/sports-data/{league_str}/r/season-{year_str}.csv")
        if (year == 9):
            # here we fix date inconsistency prevalent in the 2009-2010 data
            _df['Date'] = _df.apply(lambda x: fix_date_1(x['Date']), axis=1)
        elif (year == 18):
            _df['Date'] = _df.apply(lambda x: fix_date_2(x['Date']), axis=1)
        else:
            _df['Date'] = _df.apply(lambda x: convert_date(x['Date']), axis=1)
        dfs.append(_df)
    
    # next we combine the data into a single dataset
    ret_df = dfs[0]
    for df in dfs[1:]:
        ret_df = ret_df.append(df, ignore_index=True)
    
    return ret_df

The dataframe is then refined to only the required columns.

def fix_date_3(date):
    if date == "Present*":
        # return today's date for times marked present
        return today
    
    # certain dates have [N #] at the end so it must be removed
    indx = date.find("[")
    if indx != -1:
        date = date[:indx]
    # Converts DD MONTH YYYY to DD/MM/YY
    return dt.datetime.strptime(date, "%d %B %Y")

Since the Bundesliga information is spread out over so many different webpages, the URLs can be iterated over in a loop since the only things that change are the years. So for each year, the URL is first gathered, then read into a dataframe. The start and end date of the season are extracted and stored. Then the table with the list of managers is extracted into a dataframe and the start and end date are applied to the managers and the complete dataframe is returned.

In [93]:
def _generate_manager_table(year):
    yr = year % 100
    yr1 = "{0:02d}".format(yr)
    yr2 = "{0:02d}".format(yr + 1)
    url = f"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/20{yr1}%E2%80%93{yr2}_Bundesliga"
#     print(year, url)
    bund_tables = pd.read_html(url)
    
    season_data = bund_tables[0]
    [_start, _end] = season_data[season_data[0] == "Dates"][1].values[0].split("") # extracting the values
    start = dt.datetime.strptime(_start.strip(), "%d %B %Y") # converting to DateTime objects
    end = dt.datetime.strptime(_end.strip(), "%d %B %Y")
    
    if year == 2013 or year >= 2017:
        manager_table = bund_tables[3]
    else:
        manager_table = bund_tables[2]
    
#     print(manager_table.head())
    if year == 2015:
        # for 2015 we have to handle the nested table for managers that has
        # `Name` nested under `Manager`
        df1 = manager_table[["Team", "Manager"]]
        df1.columns = ['_'.join(tup).rstrip('_') for tup in df1.columns.values]
        df1 = df1.rename(columns={"Team_Team": "Team", "Manager_Name": "Manager"}) # renaming our columns
        df1 = df1[["Team", "Manager"]]
        manager_table = df1
        
    if year == 2018:
        # for 2018 we have to handle the nested table for managers
        df1 = manager_table[["Team", "Manager[23]"]]
        df1.columns = ['_'.join(tup).rstrip('_') for tup in df1.columns.values]
        df1 = df1.rename(columns={"Team_Team": "Team", "Manager[23]_Manager[23]": "Manager"}) # renaming our columns
        df1 = df1[["Team", "Manager"]]
        manager_table = df1
    
    if year == 2017:
        manager_table["Manager"] = manager_table["Manager[45]"]
#     if year == 2018:
#         manager_table["Manager"] = manager_table["Manager[23]"]
    if year >= 2011:
        manager_table['Head coach'] = manager_table['Manager']
    manager_table = manager_table[["Team", "Head coach"]] # including only necessary columns
    manager_table['start_date'] = start
    manager_table['end_date'] = end
    
    return manager_table

def generate_manager_table():
    dfs = []

    ret_df = dfs[0]
    for df in dfs[1:]:
#         print(df.head(5))
        ret_df = ret_df.append(df, ignore_index=True)
    
    return ret_df

def get_startdt(year):
    start_switch = {
        9: datetime.datetime(2009, 8, 29),
        10: datetime.datetime(2010, 8, 28),
        11: datetime.datetime(2011, 8, 27),
        12: datetime.datetime(2012, 8, 18),
        13: datetime.datetime(2013, 8, 17),
        14: datetime.datetime(2014, 8, 23),
        15: datetime.datetime(2015, 8, 21),
        16: datetime.datetime(2016, 8, 19),
        17: datetime.datetime(2017, 8, 18),
        18: datetime.datetime(2018, 8, 17),
    }
    return start_switch.get(year, "invalid year")

def get_enddt(year):
    end_switch = {
        9: datetime.datetime(2010, 5, 16),
        10: datetime.datetime(2011, 5, 21),
        11: datetime.datetime(2012, 5, 13),
        12: datetime.datetime(2013, 6, 1),
        13: datetime.datetime(2014, 5, 18),
        14: datetime.datetime(2015, 5, 24),
        15: datetime.datetime(2016, 5, 15),
        16: datetime.datetime(2017, 5, 21),
        17: datetime.datetime(2018, 5, 20),
        18: datetime.datetime(2019, 5, 19),
    }
    return end_switch.get(year, "invalid year")

The following function is responsible for reading in a URL, gettting the start and end date for the given season from the functions above, the extracting the remainder of the manager data from the appropriate table within the HTML. That data is then combined with the start and end dates to create a dataframe with all of the useful information and that dataframe is returned.

In [104]:
def gen_LLmanager_table(year):
    yr = year % 100
    yr1 = "{0:02d}".format(yr)
    yr2 = "{0:02d}".format(yr + 1)
    url = f"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/20{yr1}%E2%80%93{yr2}_La_Liga"
    #print(yr1, yr2, url)
    
    LL_tables = pd.read_html(url)
    startdt = get_startdt(yr)
    enddt = get_enddt(yr)
    #print(LL_tables[2])
    
    if yr == 9:
        manager_table = LL_tables[3]
    else:
        manager_table = LL_tables[2]
    
    if yr == 13:
        manager_table = manager_table[['Team', 'Head coach']]
    elif yr == 16 or yr == 19:
        manager_table = manager_table[['Team', 'Manager']]
        manager_table = manager_table.rename(columns={"Manager": "Head coach"})
    elif yr == 17 or yr == 18:
        manager_table = manager_table[['Team', 'Manager[53]']]
        manager_table = manager_table.rename(columns={"Manager[53]": "Head coach"})
    else:
        manager_table = manager_table[['Team', 'Head Coach']]
        manager_table = manager_table.rename(columns={"Head Coach": "Head coach"})
    
    manager_table['start_date'] = startdt
    manager_table['end_date'] = enddt
    
    return manager_table

Data Tidying¶

Now that all of the neccessary data has been gathered and grouped, it can now be further combined and molded to what we need for analysis reasons. There has been much data tidying done up to this point in the tutorial, much of it dealing with inconsistent dates and titles. The data tidying that will be done from this point forward will be to aid in the analysis process.

Merging the Manager Tables¶

The first part to merging the manager tables is to make sure all data between the three different leagues is uniform. The Bundesliga and LaLiga data tables sometimes contained extra data which to this tutorial is unneccessary, so it must be removed.

In [108]:
managers = pd.concat([bundesliga_managers, laliga_managers], ignore_index=True)

def clean_managers(manager):
    m = re.match(r"(.*)\(.*\)", manager)
    if m is None:
        return manager
    return m.group(1).strip()

managers['Head coach'] = managers.apply(lambda x: clean_managers(x['Head coach']), axis=1)
managers = managers.rename(columns={"Team": "team", "Head coach": "manager"})

To unify the remaining table, the premier league table must have the same column names then they can properly be merged.

def points_per_game(wins, draw, losses):
    # 3 points for wins and 1 point for a draw
    points = wins * 3 + draw
    games = wins + draw + losses
    return points / games


ppg_df['points'] = ppg_df.apply(lambda x: points_per_game(x.wins, x.draw, x.losses), axis=1)
ppg_df = ppg_df.sort_values(by=['points'], ascending=False)

Goals For-Against¶

In [131]:
def goals_for_and_against(df):
    # Home goals table is from the point of view of the home manager
    # with FTHG (Full Time Home Goals) being for the manager and
    # FTAG (Full Time Away Goals) being against the manager
    home_goals = df[["h_manager", "FTHG", "FTAG"]]
    home_goals = home_goals.rename(columns={"h_manager": "manager", "FTHG": "goals_for", "FTAG": "goals_against"})

    # Away goals is the opposite of the home goals table
    away_goals = _full_data[["a_manager", "FTHG", "FTAG"]]
    away_goals = away_goals.rename(columns={"a_manager": "manager", "FTAG": "goals_for", "FTHG": "goals_against"})
    away_goals = away_goals[["manager", "goals_for", "goals_against"]]

    # Combining the home and away data
    goals_df = pd.concat([home_goals, away_goals], ignore_index=True)

    # aggregating the total goals for
    _goals1 = goals_df.copy()[["manager", "goals_for"]]
    _goals1['goals_for'] = _goals1.groupby('manager')['goals_for'].transform('sum')
    _goals1 = _goals1.drop_duplicates()

     # aggregating the total goals against
    _goals2 = goals_df.copy()[["manager", "goals_against"]]
    _goals2['goals_against'] = _goals2.groupby('manager')['goals_against'].transform('sum')
    _goals2 = _goals2.drop_duplicates()

     # aggregating the total games    
    _goals3 = goals_df.copy()[["manager"]]
    _goals3['games'] = _goals3.groupby('manager')['manager'].transform('count')
    _goals3 = _goals3.drop_duplicates()

    # combining goals for-against and games
    _goals_table = _goals1.merge(_goals2, on='manager')
    goals_table = _goals_table.merge(_goals3, on='manager')

    # adding `net_goals_per_game` which means takes the average difference of goals
    # per game
    goals_table['net_goals_per_game'] = goals_table \
        .apply(lambda x: (x['goals_for'] - x['goals_against']) / x['games'], axis=1)
    
    goals_table = goals_table.sort_values(by=['net_goals_per_game'], ascending=False)
    return goals_table

goals_f_a = goals_for_and_against(_full_data.copy())

Generating a Model for Offensive and Defensive Minded Coaching¶

We investigate the importance of both offense and defense for coaching by standardizing an offensive and defensive score for the managers. The offensive rating is represented by the goals that are scored per game and defensive rating is the goals against per game time negative one to reward ratings near 0 (no goals against them).

In [138]:
# collecting necessary columns and generating a priliminary rating system
_manager_ratings = manager_stats.copy()[["manager", "goals_for", "goals_against", "games", "points"]]
_manager_ratings['_offensive_rating'] = _manager_ratings.apply(lambda x: x['goals_for'] / x['games'], axis=1)
# a higher defensive rating should mean less goals against so we multiply by -1
_manager_ratings['_defensive_rating'] = _manager_ratings.apply(lambda x: -1 * (x['goals_against'] / x['games']), axis=1)
_manager_ratings = _manager_ratings.drop(columns=['goals_for', 'goals_against', 'games'])

Conclusion¶

The data that was gathered and analyzed yielded some surprising names for best managers and some names that were not so surprising. Some of those names include Tito Vilanova, Pep Guardiola, Gerardo Martino, Sir Alex Ferguson, and Carlo Ancelotti. These are some of the names that are consistently shining throughout all of the data analysis.

Starting with the win-loss ratio, these men all have very high win-loss ratios but the discrepancy with this data is that Tito Vilanova and Gerardo Martino have played a fraction of games compared to some of the other names on this list. This was one of the bigger concerns with the data analysis in general, as some names might appear too high or low on the list of managers based solely upon the number of games played. After that is the points per game analysis, which is one of the most important aspects of soccer because points are what wins championships. In soccer one point is awarded for a draw, zero for a loss, and three points for a win. And the analysis shows that the same names show up for the average points per game, meaning that their record mostly consists of wins. Net goals was another thing that was analyzed, which shows how many goals they score per game and how many goals they get scored on them, on average. Unsurprisingly, the same names pop up with the highest net goals per game coming out to almost two which is very high for soccer matches. Now comparing the points and net goals showed that there is some link between the two statistics and the top managers are near and around the top of the regression line again. Next analysis was the plotting of points per game compared to the win loss ratio. This yielded data that shows that the two statistics are very closely related, with almost all points falling on the regression line. Finally we generated a model for offensive and defensive minded coaching in an attempt to see if one mindset creates more success than the other. The results showed that the two are both very important but defensive mindset seems to be constant whereas an offensive mindset can give varying results based on the opponents team. Using the data yielded from the offensive and defensive analysis, an offensive and defensive rating can be assigned to each manager and a regression model can be run to predict the points per season of each manager. The data from this yielded fairly accurate results with most residuals being only a few points off from the regression, within 7.5 points to be exact.
